child.pub-comments: Conrad (1978a) arrives at similar conclusions concerning the languages and dialects of the Arapesh family to those of Laycock (1973a), who draws on Glasgow and Loving (1964) for information on dialect distribution in Southern Arapesh (Muhiang). Conrad (1978a) agrees that Bumbita is a language different from both Southern Arapesh, which he calls Muhiang, and Mountain Arapesh, which he calls Bukiyip. At the same time, he demonstrates that Muhiang and Bukiyip consist of a single long dialect chain, and that the point of the separation of the two languages has to be somewhat arbitrarily chosen. He recognizes six dialects running from Muhiang into Bukiyip and which, on the basis of village names, could be referred to as the Balif-Albinama-Walahuta-Ilahop, Supari-Ilahita, Balanga-Ningalimba-Muwi, Iwam-Ami-Ningalemb, Womsak, and the Walihiga-Malin-Balup-Matapau-Bubuamo-Dagua dialects, with Nagipeim as the somewhat arbitrarily chosen border dialect between the two languages. These dialects are in part cross cutting with those set up by Glasgow and Loving (1964) and indicated in Laycock (1973a) even if someone of their names are comparable in Glasgow and Loving's (1964) and Conrad's (1978a) studies. Speakers: 10646

root.pub-comments: The lexical interrelationships within the families range generally from lower medium to higher medium family level, with a few instances of lower or higher lexical relationship. Within the stocks, they are generallt on the high stock level, and on the high phylum level across stock boundaries. Structurally, the relationship between most of the languages is quite close, only the Urim isolate stands structurally apart. Speakers: 79525
